<div class=3D"include4confluence-code-content">
<pre style=3D"font-size: 12px;"># Reference DataStore Retrieval API
This is a technology sample that can be used as the basis for developing an=
 API to retrieve data from Mesh DataStore.
This API demonstrates various patterns to connect to and retrieve data from=
 Datastax Astra - CassandraAPI. =20



## Dependencies YAML
Mesh Datastore is a noSQL Datastax Astra - Cassandra database for records t=
o be _written to_ and _read from_ using an information API.
To consume data from a datastore, the target datastore should be defined as=
 a dependecy in `dependencies.yaml`.
A _reader_ role and a _writer_ role are defined to provide read and read/wr=
ite access to the datastore respectively.
 `dependencies.yaml` _must_:
* Specify the name of the datastore component to read data from=20
* Specify the role of the information API. In this case _reader_ role.

**Note:** If the invoking API is not listed in the `consumption.yaml` of th=
e target database, then access will _not_ be granted even if
the corresponding `dependencies.yaml` in that component requires access to =
the datastore.

```
dependencies:
  datastores:
    - name: inf-bnkng-resrcitm-logclitcmpnt-refdatastr-v1
      roles:
        - writer
```

## Configuration

### Preferred way of reading the properties

This is the preferred way for Datastax Astra

Starting from v4, [Configuration file](https://docs.datastax.com/en/develop=
er/java-driver/4.14/manual/core/configuration/) is injected directly into t=
he container's classpath
and the driver takes care of reading the configuration directly from classp=
ath. So, the application doesn't need to read the properties.=20
For more information please read the below for more information
1. [Typesafe Config](https://github.com/lightbend/config)
2. [HOCON (Human-Optimized Config Object Notation)](https://github.com/ligh=
tbend/config/blob/main/HOCON.md)
3. [Reference Configuration](https://docs.datastax.com/en/developer/java-dr=
iver/4.14/manual/core/configuration/reference/)
4. [Simplified Cloud Configuration](https://docs.datastax.com/en/developer/=
java-driver/4.14/manual/cloud/).

Configuration required to connect to the datastore are injected by the bamb=
oo deploy pipeline by creating two files
`mesh-datastore.conf` and `mesh-datastore-secrets.conf`. These files are ma=
de available on the classpath for consumption in the API.

* `mesh-datastore.conf` for Astra extends `mesh-datastore-secrets.conf` and=
 contains the secure connect bundle, keyspace to connect.
* `mesh-datastore-secrets.conf` contains the key and secret for the datasto=
re connection.

**Sample `mesh-datastore.conf` for Astra**

```
include file("secrets/mesh-datastore-secrets.conf")

datastax-java-driver {
  basic {
    # change this to match the target keyspace
    session-keyspace =3D inf-bnkng-resrcitm-logclitcmpnt-refdatastr-v1
    cloud {
      # change this to match bundle's location; can be either a path on the=
 local filesystem
      # or a valid URL, e.g. http://acme.com/path/to/secure-connect-databas=
e_name.zip
      secure-connect-bundle =3D "/path/to/secure-connect-database_name.zip"
    }
  }
}

```

**Sample `mesh-datastore-secrets.conf`**

```
# This is a Sample secrets file for reference. Please get working credentia=
ls to test it local

datastax-java-driver {
  advanced {
    auth-provider {
      class =3D PlainTextAuthProvider
      # change below to match the appropriate credentials
      username =3D "username"
      password =3D "password"
    }
  }
}
```

## How to Connect to DataStore?

[Datastax OSS java driver](https://docs.datastax.com/en/developer/java-driv=
er/4.14/) is recommended for connecting to the datastore.
As demonstrated in `ConnectionUtils.java` in this reference API, `CqlSessio=
n` can be created and shared across the application using=20
the `CqlSessionBuilder` provided by the DataStax driver.

Configuration required for establishing cql session is injected by the depl=
oy pipelines as mentioned above.

As mentioned in the configuration section there are 2 ways to get `CqlSessi=
on`.

If using preferred way of reading the configuration, then the below code wi=
ll get `CqlSession`
```
=09CqlSession.builder().withConfigLoader(DriverConfigLoader.fromClasspath("=
mesh-datastore")).build();                  =20
```

For Spring, use `spring.data.cassandra.config=3D/path/to/mesh-datastore.con=
f` in application properties.
For more information refer [Application Properties](https://docs.spring.io/=
spring-boot/docs/current/reference/html/application-properties.html#applica=
tion-properties.data.spring.data.cassandra.config)

If you prefer to read the old way of reading the configuration from `mesh-d=
atastore.properties` and `mesh-datastore-secrets.properties` then the below=
 code should be used.
```
=09CqlSession.builder().addContactPoint(new InetSocketAddress(getHostName()=
, getPort()))
                                .withAuthCredentials(getAuthKey(), getSecre=
t())
                                .withSslContext(SSLContext.getDefault())
                                .withKeyspace(getKeySpaceName())
                                .withLocalDatacenter(getDataCenter())
                                .build();
```

## DataStax EntityMapper
DataStax driver provides a simple object mapper, which avoids most of the b=
oilerplate when converting your domain classes to and from query results.
It handles basic CRUD operations in Cassandra tables containing UDTs, colle=
ctions and all native CQL types.
This API demonstrates using Entity mapper to perform various CRUD operation=
s. All the supporting classes for the data mapper are generated
during the before compile phase. This should be enabled in the `pom.xml` by=
 adding the annotation processor to the compile configuration as below.

```
=09&lt;plugin&gt;
        &lt;artifactId&gt;maven-compiler-plugin&lt;/artifactId&gt;
        &lt;version&gt;3.8.1&lt;/version&gt;
        &lt;configuration&gt;
         &lt;annotationProcessorPaths&gt;
            &lt;path&gt;
              &lt;groupId&gt;com.datastax.oss&lt;/groupId&gt;
              &lt;artifactId&gt;java-driver-mapper-processor&lt;/artifactId=
&gt;
              &lt;version&gt;4.15.0&lt;/version&gt;
            &lt;/path&gt;

          &lt;/annotationProcessorPaths&gt;
        &lt;/configuration&gt;
      &lt;/plugin&gt;

```

## Unit Testing

[Simulacron](https://github.com/datastax/simulacron), a native protocol ser=
ver simulator for Cassandra, is used to simulate various responses from the=
=20
datastore for unit testing. As demonstrated in the junits in the reference =
API, an embedded Cassandra server and `priming DSL`=20
provided by the Simulacron API is used to prime the responses from the embe=
dded server.


## Dependencies

Include the following dependencies in `pom.xml` for DataStax Java Driver.

```
=09&lt;dependency&gt;
      &lt;groupId&gt;com.datastax.oss&lt;/groupId&gt;
      &lt;artifactId&gt;java-driver-core&lt;/artifactId&gt;
      &lt;version&gt;4.15.0&lt;/version&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;
    &lt;dependency&gt;
      &lt;groupId&gt;com.datastax.oss&lt;/groupId&gt;
      &lt;artifactId&gt;java-driver-mapper-runtime&lt;/artifactId&gt;
      &lt;version&gt;4.15.0&lt;/version&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;  =20
```
Include the following dependencies in `pom.xml` for Simulacron Embedded Ser=
ver for Unit testing.

```
&lt;!-- Unit testing dependencies --&gt;

    &lt;dependency&gt;
      &lt;groupId&gt;com.datastax.oss.simulacron&lt;/groupId&gt;
      &lt;artifactId&gt;simulacron-native-server&lt;/artifactId&gt;
      &lt;version&gt;0.11.0&lt;/version&gt;
      &lt;scope&gt;test&lt;/scope&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;
    &lt;dependency&gt;
      &lt;groupId&gt;com.datastax.oss.simulacron&lt;/groupId&gt;
      &lt;artifactId&gt;simulacron-driver-3x&lt;/artifactId&gt;
      &lt;version&gt;0.11.0&lt;/version&gt;
      &lt;scope&gt;test&lt;/scope&gt;
    &lt;/dependency&gt;
```

</pre>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
